Bug.WithStack:
I20051123-1200

Steps to reproduce:
- Consider following snippet

throw Exception();
try {
   throw Exception();
} catch (Exception exception) {
   // log
}

- Invoke Surround with Try/Catch on first throw statement
- Resulting code is

try {
   throw Exception();
} catch (Exception exception1) {
   // log
}
try {
   throw Exception();
} catch (Exception exception) {
   // log
}

-> Since the scopes of the two catch blocks are disjoint, there is no need to suggest another variable name than the one specified in the code generation settings.
Appending numbers (or other exception variable name mangling) should only be done if the name specified in the code formatter settings is already declared as a local variable.  For example, given the method

void x() throws FooException, BarException;

surrounding it's invocation with try/catch should result in:

try {
  x();
} catch (FooException ex) {
  // TODO: Handle exception.
} catch (BarException ex) {
  // TODO: Handle exception.
}

unless the variable "ex" has already been declared in the enclosing method.

Each catch block has its own scope, and it's important to recognize that.  Mangling the names unnecessarily clouds the issue.

